%  SCENARIO
% ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
\begin{scenariobox}
A marketing manager wants to know: \textbf{does advertising spend predict monthly sales?}\\[3pt]
She has data on 30 stores: how much each spent on ads (in \$1,000s) and their sales (in \$1,000s).\\[4pt]
{\bfseries\color{medblue} Y = Sales \quad|\quad X = Advertising Spend}
\end{scenariobox}

% ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
%  THE MODEL
% ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
\begin{sectionbox}{The Linear Regression Model}
The Linear Regression Model
\end{sectionbox}

\begin{center}
\begin{tcolorbox}[
  colback=white, colframe=accentblue, arc=6pt,
  boxrule=1.5pt, width=0.85\textwidth,
  halign=center, top=8pt, bottom=8pt
]
{\Large $\text{Sales} \;=\; \underset{{\color{mygreen}\text{\tiny intercept}}}{\color{mygreen}b_0} \;+\; \underset{{\color{myorange}\text{\tiny slope}}}{\color{myorange}b_1} \times \text{AdvertisingSpend} \;+\; \underset{{\color{myred}\text{\tiny error}}}{\color{myred}\varepsilon}$}

\vspace{10pt}
\begin{minipage}{0.3\textwidth}\centering
\small\color{mygreen}
\textbf{Intercept}\\
Predicted sales\\when ads = \$0
\end{minipage}
\begin{minipage}{0.35\textwidth}\centering
\small\color{myorange}
\textbf{Slope}\\
Change in sales for each\\extra \$1,000 in ads
\end{minipage}
\begin{minipage}{0.25\textwidth}\centering
\small\color{myred}
\textbf{Error}\\
What our model\\can't explain
\end{minipage}
\end{tcolorbox}
\end{center}

% ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
%  STEP 1: lm()
% ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
\begin{sectionbox}{Step 1}
Step 1: Fit the Model with \texttt{lm()}
\end{sectionbox}

The \texttt{lm()} function fits a straight line through your data:

\begin{lstlisting}
model <- lm(Sales ~ AdvertisingSpend, data = stores)
\end{lstlisting}

\begin{greenbox}[title={\faBook\ \ Reading this line:}]
\begin{tabular}{@{}llll@{}}
\texttt{\bfseries model} & \texttt{\bfseries lm(} & \texttt{\bfseries Sales \textasciitilde{} AdvertisingSpend} & \texttt{\bfseries data = stores)} \\[2pt]
{\scriptsize\color{darkgray2} Save the result} & {\scriptsize\color{darkgray2} Fit a linear} & {\scriptsize\color{darkgray2} ``Y predicted by X''} & {\scriptsize\color{darkgray2} Which data} \\
{\scriptsize\color{darkgray2} for later use} & {\scriptsize\color{darkgray2} model} & {\scriptsize\color{darkgray2} (\textasciitilde{} reads as ``depends on'')} & {\scriptsize\color{darkgray2} frame to use} \\
\end{tabular}
\end{greenbox}

\vspace{4pt}
Typing just \texttt{model} in the console shows the coefficients:

\begin{lstlisting}[style=Routput]
> model

Call:
lm(formula = Sales ~ AdvertisingSpend, data = stores)

Coefficients:
      (Intercept)  AdvertisingSpend
           12.351             2.876
\end{lstlisting}

\vspace{2pt}
\begin{minipage}[t]{0.48\textwidth}
\begin{greenbox}[title={$b_0 = 12.351$ (Intercept)}]
\small A store that spends \$0 on ads is predicted to have \$12,351 in sales.\\[2pt]
{\scriptsize\itshape\color{darkgray2} May not be meaningful if no store actually spends \$0.}
\end{greenbox}
\end{minipage}
\hfill
\begin{minipage}[t]{0.48\textwidth}
\begin{orangebox}[title={$b_1 = 2.876$ (Slope)}]
\small Each additional \$1,000 in ads is associated with \$2,876 more in sales.\\[2pt]
{\scriptsize\itshape\color{darkgray2} This is the key business insight!}
\end{orangebox}
\end{minipage}

\vspace{6pt}
\begin{tipbox}
{\bfseries\color{mypurple} Tip:} You can also get just the coefficients with: \texttt{coef(model)}
\end{tipbox}

